{{Quote|Those of us at ILM were aiming for reality, or something beyond reality in this movie. Something that has life, a spark, and a quality that's bigger than life.|Ken Ralston|<ref name="Bantha">{{BanthaCite|issue=21|article=Special Effects}}</ref>}}
'''Kenneth Ralston''' was a concept artist and visual effects artist for [[Star Wars]] [[original trilogy]].

==Biography==
{{Quote|His maneuvering of the TIE fighter and the ''Falcon'' show his great understanding of the need for timing , motion, and life within the shot.|Dennis Muren, on Ranston's talent|<ref name="TESB40">''[[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back: Special 40th Anniversary Collector's Edition]]''</ref>}}
[[File:KenRalston-TESB40.png|thumb|left|250px|Ralston moving a battle-damaged TIE fighter model]]
Ken Ralston was one of the original employees of [[Industrial Light & Magic]], originally hired by [[Dennis Muren]] to help [[George Lucas]].<ref name="Tippett">{{SWArchive|url=episode-iv/bts/article/f20040602/index.html|text=Phil Tippett: Hands-On Effects}}</ref> He served as one of three assistant cameramen for the Miniature and Optical Effects Unit on [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']] and one of two effects cameramen for the same unit on [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']]. He went on to serve as Visual Effects Supervisor for [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']].

Ralston was responsible for placing the tennis shoe and [[Potato/Legends|potato]] [[easter egg]]s in the [[original trilogy]].<ref name="HB 61">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/production/beacon61.html|text=Homing Beacon #61: Episode II Easter Eggs}}</ref>

Ralston is one of the signers of the limited edition release of the upcoming limited edition hardcover ''[[The Art of Ralph McQuarrie]]''.<ref name="Dreams">{{WebCite|url=http://www.dreamsandvisionspress.com|text=dreams & visions press|archivedate=20210331154605}}</ref> He has also appeared with interviews in ''[[Lucasfilm Magazine 41]]'' and [[Star Wars Insider 67|''Star Wars Insider'' 67]], along with providing interior artwork for ''[[Monsters and Aliens from George Lucas]]''.

Additionally, Ralston visual effects work has won him a total of five [[Wikipedia:Academy Award|Academy Awards]] and five [[Wikipedia:British Academy Award|British Academy Awards]].<ref name="Sony">{{WebCite|url=http://www.sonypictures.com/imageworks/company/bios/kralston.html|text=Ken Ralston|work=Sony Pictures Imagework|archivedate=20031017142545}}</ref>

